In general, the argument function  does not commute with itself at
different points . This is not (only) due to non-Abelian charges
which might be included in the vector field  but to the non-commutative
nature of the elements of the Clifford algebra. Thus the solution of
equation () is not an exponential function 
but a path-ordered exponential:

G_H[g_H(nx, ny,)]
=
g_H(nx,ny,).
A sufficient but not necessary condition for its existence is that the norm
of the integrand in equation () is bounded.
It has to be noted that the invariance of an integral under simultaneous
exchange of the integration boundaries and inversion of the sign cannot be
used in equation () because the path ordering would be
reversed.
