exponent . Thus, its convergence becomes slow not only for rapid
changes of the gauge field but also for large values of the field and/or
large energies. Even the free propagator then needs
many terms to be approximated sufficiently well.




Space-like coordinates 

The general solution scheme for a classical field depending on an arbitrary
rectilinear coordinate  leading to equation () with the
argument () always yields a Green's function
whose boundary conditions are given on a plane normal to . 
Boundary conditions for propagators are given on surfaces with
time-like normal vectors . Hence, for a field only depending on the 
-coordinate (), only a Green's function but not a
propagator is given by equations () and (). 

