Fermion-antifermion pair production 

Here the results for the full propagator in an external field depending on
one rectilinear time-like coordinate are applied to the problem of particle
production due to vacuum polarisation. First it is argued where such a
propagator is of use in describing the physics of fermions in a heavy-ion
collision. Second, a detailed comparison of the different approximation
schemes with the full solution for a given model field is presented.

This calculation can be understood in a twofold way. On the one hand the
field could be really an external field in the sense of the production of
particles via vacuum polarisation. It is determined by the dynamics of the
physical system without taking the back reaction of the particle creation into
account. This field is used to calculate how many particles
would be produced in its presence. This approach is justified if the
process of particle production constitutes merely a small perturbation.
Whether this condition is fulfilled has to be checked afterwards.

On the other hand, the field could already be a self-consistent solution of a
system of equations. For this solution for the classical field one would like 
to know how many particles were created in the process. In the present
scenario such a set of equations would include the Yang-Mills equations with
the expectation value for the current of produced fermions and antifermions
:

^F _ -i[A ^,F _ ]
=
<J^>,
with the gauge field  and the corresponding field tensor





in the adjoint representation.
The expectation value for the current can be obtained from
the causal propagator:

<J^>tr ^G_C(x,x),


where the trace is only running over the matrices of the Clifford algebra
and with the definition:




with .
Higher-order radiative corrections are suppressed by powers of the
coupling constant which are not compensated by powers of the
classical field.
The causal propagator can be reexpressed as a linear combination of the 
retarded, the advanced and the on-shell propagator:

G_C(x,y)=1 2 [G_R(x,y)+G_A(x,y)+G_S(x,y)].
The advanced propagator can be obtained from the homogeneous solution
 for the equation of motion for the Dirac Green's
function by the relation:

i^0 G_A(x_0,y_0,k)
=
-(y_0-x_0)G_H(x_0,y_0,k).
The on-shell propagator can be reexpressed in terms of the retarded and
advanced one-particle scattering operators:

