General resummation formula 

In general, a path-ordered exponential with an integrand depending on a
single variable  can be rewritten in the following way:

^x_0 _y_0 d_0[B(_0)+C(_0)]
&=&
_l=0 ^^x_0 _y_0 d_1^_1 _y_0 d_2...^_l-1  _y_0 d_l
& &
__1 ^x_0 d_0 B(_0)
C(_1)
&&
__2 ^_1 d_0B(_0)
C(_2)
&&
...
&&
__l ^_l-1  d_0 B(_0)
C(_l)
&&
_y_0 ^_l d_0 B(_0).
Making use of the group property valid for the present path-ordered 
exponentials:

_z_0 ^x_0 d_0 B(_0)
_y_0 ^z_0 d_0 B(_0)
=
_y_0 ^x_0 d_0 B(_0)
the above equation can be reexpressed as:

&&^x_0 _y_0 d_0[B(_0)+C(_0)]
=
=
&&^x_0 _y_0 d_0B(_0)
_l=0 ^^x_0 _y_0 d_1^_1 _y_0 d_2...^_l-1  _y_0 d_l
&&_x_0 ^y_0 d_0 B(_0)
__1 ^x_0 d_0 B(_0)
C(_1)
^_1 _y_0 d_0 B(_0)
&&_x_0 ^y_0 d_0 B(_0)
__2 ^x_0 d_0 B(_0)
C(_2)
^_2 _y_0 d_0 B(_0)
...
&&_x_0 ^y_0 d_0 B(_0)
__l ^x_0 d_0 B(_0)
C(_l)
^_l _y_0 d_0 B(_0)
=
=
&&^x_0 _y_0 d_0 B(_0)
&&[
_x_0 ^y_0 dz_0 B(z_0).
&&     ._x_0 ^y_0 d_0
__0 ^x_0 dz_0 B(z_0)
C(_0)
^_0 _y_0 dz_0 B(z_0)
].
Again, by virtue of the group property the most compact form is given by:

&&^x_0 _y_0 d_0[B(_0)+C(_0)]
=
=
&&^x_0 _y_0 d_0 B(_0)
&&[
^x_0 _y_0 d_0
__0 ^y_0 dz_0 B(z_0)
C(_0)
^_0 _y_0 dz_0 B(z_0)
].
Summarising, 
more general resummations are possible in which the dominant quantity can be
chosen arbitrarily. Further, the above steps can be repeated so as to 
resum the obtained quantity several times, e.g. after splitting 
into a dominant part and a deviation.

The above result can also be obtained in another way. Write the Fourier
transformed Dirac equation in a generic form, where the dependence
on  will not be denoted in the following:

[d dx_0 +B(x_0)+C(x_0)] G_H(x_0,y_0)=0.
With the ansatz

 G_H(x_0,y_0)=U(x_0,y_0)G_H(x_0,y_0)
and the product rule for differentiation one obtains:

[d dx_0 U(x_0,y_0)]G_H(x_0,y_0)
+
U(x_0,y_0)[d dx_0 G_H(x_0,y_0)]
+
+
[B(x_0)+C(x_0)]U(x_0,y_0)G_H(x_0,y_0)
=0.
When postulating that  satisfies the differential equation

d dx_0 U(x_0,y_0)+B(x)U(x_0,y_0)=0,
the above expression reduces to:

U(x_0,y_0)[d dx_0 G_H(x_0,y_0)]
+
C(x_0)U(x_0,y_0)G_H(x_0,y_0)
=0.
This formula can be transformed by multiplying with  from the
left:

[d dx_0 G_H(x_0,y_0)]
+
U^-1 (x_0,y_0)C(x_0)U(x_0,y_0)G_H(x_0,y_0)
=0.
As has been shown above, the solutions for the last equation and equation 
() are given by

G(x_0,y_0)
=
^x_0 _y_0 d_0
U^-1 (_0,y_0)C(_0)U(_0,y_0)

and

U(x_0,y_0)
=
^x_0 _y_0 d_0
B(_0) 
,
respectively. Making use of the group property () the last line 
of equation () is reproduced. These derivations can be repeated
for any variable . Only for  the Dirac equation cannot be written in
the generic form ().




